      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0599">
               <p>An Independent minister, Doddridge was chosen in <date when="1729">1729</date> (on
                  the recommendation of <persName>Isaac Watts</persName>) as the first tutor of a
                  new academy for training dissenting ministers. A few months later the institution
                  was moved to <placeName>Northampton</placeName>, where Doddridge was ordained as
                  minister of Castle Hill church. His approach to his work was liberal and
                  scholarly, interdenominational and evangelical. So lavishly did <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0964.xml"/>Lady Huntingdon</persName> sing his praises
                  that <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> sought
                  Doddridge&apos;s advice on an anthology of evangelical theology that eventually
                  appeared as his <hi rend="italic">Christian Library</hi>. See <hi rend="italic"
                     >DEB</hi>, 314–15; <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Dictionary</hi>, 98.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
